<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="chp5sec1" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Quadratic Residues</title>

  <p> </p>
  
  <definition xml:id="definition-quadratic_residues">
    <title>Quadratic Residues</title>
    <statement>
        <p>
            If <m>p</m> is an odd prime and <m>a</m> relative prime to <m>p</m>, then <m>a</m> is a <term>quadratic residue modulo <m>p</m></term> if there exists an integer <m>x</m> such that
            <m>
                x^2 \equiv a \pmod{p}
            </m>
            In this case, we also say that <m>a</m> is a <term>square modulo <m>p</m></term>.  Otherwise, <m>a</m> is a <term>quadratic non-residue modulo <m>p</m></term>.
        </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>

  <proposition xml:id="proposition-negative_one_is_a_square_modulo_p_congruent_to_1_mod_4">
  <title>Negative one is a square modulo <m>p</m> when <m>p \equiv 1 \pmod{4}</m></title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      If <m>p</m> is an odd prime, then <m>-1</m> is a square modulo <m>p</m> if and only if <m>p \equiv 1 \pmod{4}</m>.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <proof>
    <p>
      Try a direct proof.  First show the backward direction.  Then <m>p=4k+1</m> (why???).  Write <m>(p-1)!=(1 \cdot 2 \cdots (2k))\cdot((p-(2k)) \cdots (p-1))</m>.  Deduce <m>(p-1)! \equiv (2k)!^2 \pmod{p}</m>.  Now show the forward direction.  If <m>-1</m> is a square modulo <m>p</m>, then there exists an integer <m>x</m> such that <m>x^2 \equiv -1 \pmod{p}</m>.  Raise both sides to the power of <m>(p-1)/2</m>.  Show that <m>(-1)^{(p-1)/2} \equiv 1 \pmod{p}</m> and deduce that <m>4 \mid p-1</m>.
      You may find  <xref ref="definition-congruence"/>, <xref ref="proposition-wilsons_theorem"/>, <xref ref="proposition-fermats_little_theorem"/> useful.
    </p>
  </proof>
</proposition>


<sage>
<input>
for p in prime_range(1,100):
  if p%4==1:
    i = factorial((p-1)/2)%p
    print(p,i,i^2%p-p)
</input>
<output>
</output>
</sage>

</section>